	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>about OAM evaluation</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />- <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php?title=PPU_sprite_evaluation" class="postlink">The wiki</a> says:
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">Cycles 64-255: Sprite evaluation<br /><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; * On even cycles, data is read from &#40;primary&#41; OAM </div>
<br />- How exactly does such OAM read work? Will it read like OAM[n][0] or something? Could someone clarify it?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Fri Jan 14, 2011 9:00 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Reads happen on even dots from x=64-255; writes happen on odd dots. The first pair copies OAM[n][0] (the Y coordinate) to the next free slot in secondary OAM. If this is in range, the next 6 dots are spent copying the other three attributes to the same slot in secondary OAM; otherwise, those are skipped and the PPU moves directly to n+1. Of these 192 dots, only 176 are strictly necessary in the worst case: 56 out-of-range reads at 2 dots each followed by eight in-range reads at 8 dots each.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


